    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-11-08T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-11-08T00:00:00-05:00" n="1279"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1279">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 612.1123/10.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé d’Affaires</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1772.]</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-11-08">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 8, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to the Department’s telegraphic
                    instruction of October 23, 1 p.m., relative to the closure of ports of Mexico by
                    executive or legislative order, I have the honor to report that I have received
                    a note from the Mexican Foreign Office which states to the effect that in view
                    of the fact that the conditions at the port of Vera Cruz are now changed, the
                    Foreign Office believes that the matter may be considered as terminated.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Montgomery Schuyler.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
